WEBVTT

00:00.034 --> 00:04.480
The following message by Alistair Begg is made available by Truth For Life.

00:04.500 --> 00:08.464
For more information visit us online at truthforlife.org.

00:09.926 --> 00:16.334
I invite you to follow along as I read two brief passages from the New Testament.

00:17.055 --> 00:25.225
First from Matthew chapter 7 and from verse 7, where Jesus says, ask and it will be given to you.

00:25.265 --> 00:29.010
Seek and you will find, knock,

00:29.314 --> 00:30.676
and it will be open to you.

00:31.617 --> 00:36.282
For everyone who asks, receives, and the one who seeks finds.

00:37.504 --> 00:41.268
And to the one who knocks, it will be opened.

00:41.288 --> 00:45.794
Or which of you, if his son asks him for bread, will give him a stone.

00:46.735 --> 00:51.200
Or if he asks for a fish, will give him a serpent.

00:51.221 --> 00:59.090
If you then, who are evil, know how to give good gifts to your children, how much more will your father

00:59.170 --> 01:03.515
who is in heaven, give good things to those who ask Him.

01:04.997 --> 01:19.416
And then in Ephesians 3 from verse 14, all rights, for this reason, I bow my knees before the Father, from whom every family in heaven and on earth is named.

01:20.457 --> 01:27.666
That according to the riches of His glory, He may grant you to be strengthened with power through His Spirit,

01:27.874 --> 01:54.130
in your inner being, so that Christ may dwell in your hearts through faith, that you being rooted and grounded in love may have strength to comprehend with all the saints what is the breadth and length and height and depth, and to know the love of Christ that surpasses knowledge, that you may be filled with all the fullness of God.

01:55.138 --> 02:12.136
Now to him who is able to do far more abundantly than all that we ask or think, according to the power at work within us, to him be glory in the church and in Christ Jesus throughout all generations forever and ever.

02:12.176 --> 02:13.478
Amen.

02:14.679 --> 02:16.842
And just a brief prayer before we look at this.

02:18.343 --> 02:21.366
Father, what we know not teach us.

02:23.289 --> 02:24.690
What we have not

02:25.410 --> 02:28.353
Give us what we are not.

02:29.394 --> 02:29.895
Make us.

02:31.076 --> 02:32.798
For your son's sake, we pray.

02:33.920 --> 02:34.280
Amen.

02:36.162 --> 02:38.345
Well, it is a wonderful privilege to be here with you.

02:38.745 --> 02:44.271
I've found it difficult to realize that the threshold of entry was the age of 18.

02:44.852 --> 02:53.842
And to go back to when I might have qualified as an 18-year-old to get in here, I have to go back some 58 years.

02:54.242 --> 02:57.447
So it's fun to be around the young folks.

02:58.629 --> 03:04.798
And I have been delighted to be entrusted with the privilege of our topic for this evening.

03:05.639 --> 03:07.001
I don't know who came up with it.

03:07.021 --> 03:10.586
It has a kind of piper-esque dimension to it.

03:11.608 --> 03:14.793
And I want to make sure that we understand the topic.

03:15.995 --> 03:17.857
First of all, we know who God is.

03:18.759 --> 03:23.666
That he is plural, he's powerful, he's perfect.

03:24.034 --> 03:25.215
and he's praiseworthy.

03:26.236 --> 03:31.521
Also, we understand the word generosity for unselfish kindness.

03:32.642 --> 03:38.828
We understand extravagance, that which goes beyond why it might be expected.

03:39.929 --> 03:48.277
And the word entreating, perhaps you haven't used it recently, perhaps you haven't found it necessary.

03:49.358 --> 03:53.842
It means more than asking, another word might be beseeching

03:53.922 --> 03:55.164
or imploring.

03:55.184 --> 04:10.808
If you know the story of Ruth and you read it as I did in the King James Version, you will remember that Ruth says to Naomi, entreat me not to leave thee or to return from following after thee.

04:12.010 --> 04:22.066
So, entreating the extravagant generosity of God is in short order a talk about prayer.

04:23.682 --> 04:26.326
Why didn't it just say a talk on prayer?

04:27.408 --> 04:29.371
Because I wouldn't have been such a good title.

04:30.112 --> 04:36.122
And one of the evidences of being adopted into God's family is that we actually pray.

04:37.144 --> 04:45.757
You remember in Romans 8 Paul says this, he says, and the Spirit of God in our hearts enables us to say, Abba Father.

04:47.220 --> 04:51.186
In all of our conversations today, as we've spoken with one another,

04:51.298 --> 04:55.944
We have in our words revealed essentially what's going on in our minds.

04:57.306 --> 05:05.916
But when we pray in the secrecy of our lives to God, we're actually declaring what's going on in our hearts.

05:07.318 --> 05:10.082
And prayer is a spiritual discipline.

05:10.142 --> 05:12.925
It is a privilege and it is a challenge.

05:13.446 --> 05:19.954
You'll remember the disciples who lived in the company of Jesus needed the encouragement that Jesus gave to them.

05:20.034 --> 05:22.477
which is why we read from Matthew 7.

05:23.478 --> 05:31.749
And here we are, many of you arriving here for this event, aware of the amazing generosity of your parents over Christmas.

05:32.830 --> 05:44.285
And what we're discovering is that parental generosity doesn't even come close to matching the extravagant dimensions of God's provision for his children.

05:44.325 --> 05:48.210
The challenge in it should not be evaded.

05:48.482 --> 06:08.764
Charles Simian, who was the minister in Cambridge for 54 years, on one occasion, pointed out to his congregation that it was easier for a pastor to preach and study for five hours than to pray for his people for one half hour.

06:10.106 --> 06:17.554
And so we do need the encouragement and the pattern that is provided for us, certainly in Jesus,

06:17.762 --> 06:20.346
and definitely here in Paul.

06:20.866 --> 06:32.843
You remember that when people asked Jesus about praying, he told them, I don't want you to be like those folks who posture in their public displays of devotion to God.

06:33.323 --> 06:38.911
I don't want you to be like those who just prattle on and on, adding word upon word.

06:40.353 --> 06:46.962
Quite famously, Whitfield on one occasion commented to a friend about a brother of his,

06:47.170 --> 06:52.998
who he said prayed in his company and prayed Fitfield into a blessing.

06:54.000 --> 06:59.988
And then he kept praying so long that he prayed him right back out of the blessing itself.

07:01.190 --> 07:03.012
So we must be cautious.

07:04.074 --> 07:12.385
Now all that by way of introducing the text, we come to this text and I want us just to consider three straightforward questions.

07:13.467 --> 07:15.730
What does Paul ask?

07:16.226 --> 07:17.347
That's the entreaty.

07:17.387 --> 07:21.191
On what basis does he ask?

07:21.211 --> 07:22.532
That's the generosity.

07:22.593 --> 07:25.636
And to what end does he ask?

07:26.256 --> 07:28.318
And that is the glory.

07:29.680 --> 07:32.603
So I will spend longer on the first than on the other two.

07:33.123 --> 07:38.709
I mention that to you now because you may be extrapolating from the length of time I spend on the first.

07:39.089 --> 07:41.292
And you're saying, we're going to be here for about midnight.

07:41.772 --> 07:43.634
Relax, you will be fine.

07:44.578 --> 07:46.981
He's addressing them as the family of God.

07:47.142 --> 07:54.872
At the end of chapter two, he describes them as citizens, as saints, as stones that are being built into the temple of God.

07:55.533 --> 08:00.200
And you will notice that he approaches God on his knees.

08:01.061 --> 08:10.514
For this reason, he says, the wonder of all that you've done in the gospel and in the church, I bow my knees.

08:11.266 --> 08:27.114
All would have been well aware of the Psalm 95, which begins, O come, let us worship and bow down, let us kneel before the Lord our Maker, for we are His people and the sheep of His pasture.

08:27.995 --> 08:36.370
Customarily Jewish men stood to pray, and therefore it is a matter of some significance that we have this picture of Paul.

08:36.706 --> 08:53.208
He comes boldly because he has access, as he says in verse 12, but the boldness of his access is combined with the humility of his posture, because he recognizes that he is coming to a God who is great and awesome.

08:54.150 --> 09:00.338
He, in comparison, we, in comparison, are small and we're finite.

09:01.314 --> 09:23.769
And therefore, when we draw near to God in worship, as Ecclesiastes reminds us, we should take care of how we come so that we guard against presumption or a casual familiarity that is often the result of entertaining big views of ourselves and small views of God.

09:24.791 --> 09:29.618
Some years ago, Peggy Noonan, who writes in the Wall Street Journal, made this comment,

09:30.274 --> 09:38.223
For 30 years, the self-esteem movement told the young they are perfect in every way.

09:39.404 --> 09:48.634
It's yielding something new in history, an entire generation, with no proper sense of inadequacy.

09:49.935 --> 09:51.757
The self-assured need not pray.

09:52.418 --> 09:55.081
We're just perceived on the basis of what we know.

09:55.141 --> 09:59.826
It is when we're aware of our own inadequacy and the grandeur of God.

10:00.130 --> 10:02.012
that we approach as Paul approaches.

10:03.414 --> 10:05.176
But what is it that he prays for?

10:06.318 --> 10:10.583
Perhaps we should ask the other question, what is it that he doesn't pray for?

10:10.643 --> 10:17.032
You'll notice that in his prayer, he's not preoccupied with material things.

10:17.652 --> 10:28.306
He's not preoccupied with his own predicament, not because those things weren't present or weren't valid, but because they weren't the issue.

10:29.826 --> 10:34.833
Jesus says to His disciples, why are you worrying about this and about this?

10:35.414 --> 10:40.641
Seek first the kingdom of God and His righteousness and all these things will be added to you.

10:41.662 --> 10:46.589
Now Paul understood that the people in Ephesus were real people like us this evening.

10:47.250 --> 10:59.026
They had concerns about marriage or about singleness, about parenting, about enjoying life, about welfare, about employment and all these other things.

10:59.618 --> 11:04.883
But there is no mention of these matters as he prays for them now.

11:05.724 --> 11:09.868
Again, not because they are in presence, but because that's not the issue.

11:11.169 --> 11:16.554
Praying about health incidentally is very rare in the Bible.

11:17.415 --> 11:28.946
Some of you may have heard Don Carson years ago commenting on this and saying that at the average church prayer meeting, more time is spent by people seeking to keep the saints

11:29.154 --> 11:33.960
out of heaven rather than sinners out of hell.

11:35.182 --> 11:37.806
So then, if he's not doing that, what is this entreaty?

11:38.366 --> 11:48.860
It's there in the text that according to the riches of his glory, he may grant you to be strengthened with power through his spirit in your inner being.

11:49.621 --> 11:51.224
In your inner being.

11:51.244 --> 11:53.687
Do you have an inner being?

11:53.727 --> 11:56.050
Yes, of course you do.

11:56.962 --> 12:03.931
Our inner being is our essential self, hidden from view yet real.

12:05.093 --> 12:08.978
It is the sharpest focus of our existence.

12:10.320 --> 12:17.509
Our inner being, if you like, is what will remain when our bodies are laid to rest in the grave.

12:18.630 --> 12:21.394
And here is the realm that Paul

12:21.570 --> 12:26.938
focuses in his prayer that you would be strengthened with power in your inner being.

12:27.879 --> 12:30.383
In other words, this is the real core.

12:31.645 --> 12:41.359
Now you can tell from looking at me that I don't know much about core or about free weights or about anything at all, but I am familiar with the terminology that people are talking about.

12:41.700 --> 12:45.886
Your golf swing is not directly related to your musculature.

12:46.426 --> 12:48.850
It's directly related to your core.

12:49.314 --> 12:54.962
And sure, a tremendous amount of time and energy is spent, understandably, on the core.

12:55.764 --> 13:02.974
Well, let me tell you, we're wasting away while our inner self is being renewed day by day.

13:03.034 --> 13:05.418
And I assume you have grasped this.

13:06.059 --> 13:18.898
Otherwise, why would you be here for these few days unless you recognize that the real you fashioned according to the plan and purpose of God, the core of your existence,

13:19.042 --> 13:21.985
is the direct concern of your heavenly Father.

13:22.565 --> 13:34.217
When Paul writes to Timothy, he says to him, physical fitness has a certain value, but spiritual fitness is essential both for this life and for the life to come.

13:35.538 --> 13:47.890
If you doubt this, you could go to your bedroom before you fall asleep for the night and just read Ecclesiastes 12, where you have this amazing picture of a body being like a house.

13:48.194 --> 13:51.138
that is becoming increasingly dilapidated.

13:51.178 --> 14:05.097
Now, when you're your age, you don't think anything of this, that's why the writer says, remember your creator in the days of your youth before the days of trouble come when all of the things start to collapse.

14:05.838 --> 14:17.714
It is quite humorous, actually, when you have to ask for reading glasses, when your hands begin to tremble, when you have to have your meniscus repaired,

14:17.794 --> 14:31.571
when your legs give way, when you have inadequate occlusion, that your top teeth can't meet your bottom teeth, and you have a problem there, when you drag yourself eventually along the street like a grasshopper.

14:33.293 --> 14:34.154
What a picture.

14:35.716 --> 14:36.758
It's in the Bible.

14:36.798 --> 14:38.540
It's your future.

14:42.345 --> 14:46.610
There will be a day when you will go to CVS,

14:47.266 --> 14:52.633
and go down aisles that today you can't imagine why they even have the aisles.

14:54.836 --> 15:01.866
And you'll find yourself asking for things that people like me could be heard asking for when you bumped into us.

15:03.228 --> 15:08.915
Why does Paul entreat God on their behalf in this way?

15:09.496 --> 15:13.261
Why is he so concerned about their inner being?

15:13.581 --> 15:16.946
He tells us in verse 17, show that

15:17.058 --> 15:23.348
a purpose clause, so that Christ may dwell in your hearts through faith.

15:24.610 --> 15:40.153
The strengthening work of the Holy Spirit, enabling us and assuring us, is actually in conjunction with what the Westminster Confession calls the ordinary use of the means of grace.

15:41.095 --> 15:45.842
Which means this, that the work of the Spirit of God within our hearts

15:46.082 --> 15:56.398
as we pray to God and as we look to Him, we do so hearing His voice as we hear it from the Scriptures.

15:56.418 --> 16:06.454
We do so engaged in His body where we belong, and we do so having access to His ear.

16:06.494 --> 16:08.518
Hence our prayer.

16:10.000 --> 16:13.906
So that Christ does not take up residence in our lives,

16:14.370 --> 16:17.875
simply to cheer us or to soothe us.

16:19.157 --> 16:22.322
He comes to reign in our lives.

16:23.544 --> 16:25.247
You remember C.S.

16:25.327 --> 16:32.317
Lewis uses again that picture of a house where he says, imagine yourself as a living house.

16:33.820 --> 16:36.564
God comes to rebuild that house.

16:37.886 --> 16:43.154
At first, perhaps you can understand what he's doing, basic repairs.

16:44.002 --> 16:51.092
But then he starts knocking the house about in a way that hurts abominably and doesn't make sense.

16:52.494 --> 16:53.755
What is the explanation?

16:55.077 --> 17:02.267
You thought, writes Lewis, you were going to be made into a decent little cottage, but he is building a palace.

17:03.328 --> 17:07.374
He intends to come and live in it himself.

17:09.837 --> 17:13.522
What we have here is the issue of

17:13.730 --> 17:22.183
God's authority as he comes to reign and God's intimacy with us as he meets with us.

17:24.467 --> 17:41.554
I have friends who think that I am a dreadful sentimentalist for all kinds of reasons and they may be right because I actually find some volume in an old song that seldom sung which begins, I know, it's got a kind of

17:42.178 --> 17:44.442
Thomas can cavefield to it, I think.

17:45.103 --> 17:49.750
I come to the garden alone while the dew is still on the roses.

17:50.732 --> 17:57.143
And the voice I hear falling on my ear, the Son of God, disposes.

17:58.224 --> 18:00.568
And then it says, and he walks with me.

18:02.532 --> 18:03.734
And he talks with me.

18:03.794 --> 18:08.882
And he tells me, I am his own.

18:11.138 --> 18:13.761
You say, well, is that sheer sentimentalism?

18:14.402 --> 18:33.883
Or is it not closer to what Jesus is saying to his disciples in the upper room discourse when in John 14, he tells them, listen, you follow along the road I've set you on and you will discover that I will come to you and I will show myself to you.

18:33.903 --> 18:40.690
In verse 23, he says, we will come to him and make our

18:40.898 --> 18:42.359
home with Him.

18:44.321 --> 18:44.662
Why?

18:45.262 --> 18:51.629
Because of the extravagant generosity of our heavenly Father.

18:53.130 --> 19:01.319
Now you will notice, too, that he then says, your condition is being rooted and grounded in love.

19:02.500 --> 19:08.786
It's a horticultural metaphor, followed by an architectural metaphor, rooted

19:08.962 --> 19:18.431
familiar material, I am the vine, you are the branches and so on, and the architectural picture of being built into a spiritual temple.

19:19.752 --> 19:27.820
The imagined thing is that we were once alienated from God, we were hostile, we were hopeless.

19:29.101 --> 19:35.307
And what he's been saying to these Ephesian believers is that God has done something absolutely dramatic.

19:35.788 --> 19:37.970
He has made one new man

19:38.082 --> 19:48.158
out of the two, these believers that were present there, are brought together by the power of God in the gospel of the Lord Jesus Christ.

19:49.380 --> 19:50.622
Now, listen carefully.

19:51.543 --> 20:03.001
Only in Christ are the longings of our generation for hope, for humanity, for peace, and for unity.

20:03.482 --> 20:06.226
Only in Jesus Christ are they answered.

20:07.554 --> 20:21.351
It is perfectly understandable that imagine by Lenin became the mantra of an entire continent.

20:21.371 --> 20:22.412
What are they longing for?

20:22.452 --> 20:23.433
What are they hoping for?

20:24.074 --> 20:35.268
The same thing that Michael Jackson and Springsteen and the rest of them got together, nighttime in Hollywood, to sing, we are the world, we are the people.

20:36.249 --> 20:37.330
Actually, in that

20:37.410 --> 20:43.199
song they sing, we are saving our own selves.

20:45.222 --> 20:46.223
Well, how are they doing?

20:47.645 --> 20:54.997
Or even in a more trivial level, I'd like to teach the world to sing in perfect harmony.

20:55.818 --> 21:01.927
I'd like to buy the world a Coke and keep it company.

21:01.947 --> 21:04.191
You're going to go out into this generation.

21:04.711 --> 21:06.514
You are out in this generation.

21:06.882 --> 21:17.412
a generation that longs for things that are understandable and yet has not been able to discover the key that unlocks the reality for them.

21:17.892 --> 21:36.690
And you have the privilege as God by his spirit dwells in your inner man, strengthens you with power, equips you, encourages you so that you rooted and grounded in love for Jesus and for the people of God you may then

21:37.122 --> 22:06.802
go on to have strength, to comprehend with all the saints, this is verse 18, to comprehend, this is the second part of his entreaty, one that we've just looked at, and now that you may have strength to comprehend with all the saints what is the breadth and length and height and depth that surpasses knowledge, that you may be filled with all the fullness

22:06.946 --> 22:07.647
of God.

22:08.829 --> 22:33.362
Now, if you just take that and write it in your journal tonight and think about it before you go to sleep, clearly what Paul is asking of God is something larger and greater than our own personal preoccupations, our own longings for self-fulfillment, our own concerns legitimate to one degree and yet overreaching in another.

22:33.698 --> 22:36.883
Paul is taking us in another direction altogether.

22:36.943 --> 22:42.832
He's not asking, you will notice, that we should love God more.

22:43.613 --> 22:51.445
We always want to love God more, but that we should have the power to grasp God's love for us.

22:53.508 --> 22:55.210
Paul, of course, understood this.

22:56.592 --> 23:02.962
He was an arch enemy of Jesus and the church, and yet his life was changed, wasn't it?

23:03.618 --> 23:04.860
He understood mercy.

23:05.361 --> 23:06.542
He understood grace.

23:07.464 --> 23:09.807
This is true of anyone who really becomes a Christian.

23:10.408 --> 23:19.201
We may not be lying by the side of the road, struck blind by a great light, but when you become a Christian, you will have a whole new view of Jesus.

23:20.303 --> 23:27.013
You will have a whole new view of the people who love Jesus, and you will have a whole new view of mercy.

23:28.174 --> 23:30.578
And it's out of the fullness of that reality.

23:30.882 --> 23:31.983
that he speaks in this way.

23:32.364 --> 23:36.389
Spatial objects are, you usually say, the length of breadth or the height.

23:36.990 --> 23:38.772
Here you will notice, it's fourfold.

23:39.293 --> 23:40.635
I'm not sure what this means.

23:41.436 --> 23:45.722
Or what he's saying, I know what he's saying, he's saying, it's overarching all of this.

23:47.143 --> 23:55.154
Ferguson, my friend, says, he may not only be thinking in terms of the length and breadth that reaches to the four corners of the earth,

23:57.026 --> 24:06.080
but perhaps involving contemplating the depth through which the Son of God stooped and the heights to which he has been exalted.

24:06.100 --> 24:12.309
That you might know the love that surpasses knowledge.

24:13.190 --> 24:14.532
That's a paradox, isn't it?

24:15.234 --> 24:17.437
Knowing what is unknowable.

24:18.498 --> 24:23.506
It's far easier to sing about it than it is actually to articulate it or to define it.

24:24.098 --> 24:27.763
When Paul writes to the Corinthians at one point, he says, I has not seen.

24:27.803 --> 24:31.067
It's invisible, nor ear-haired.

24:31.668 --> 24:32.469
It's inaudible.

24:33.831 --> 24:36.575
Nor has it penetrated the imagination.

24:36.675 --> 24:37.856
It is inconceivable.

24:38.297 --> 24:41.281
The things that God has prepared for those who love him.

24:41.982 --> 24:46.148
But he says, this he has revealed to us by the Holy Spirit.

24:47.129 --> 24:50.994
And here now he prays for this fledgling church in Ephesus.

24:51.234 --> 24:56.341
that this might be their experience as a result of God's generosity.

24:57.042 --> 25:03.631
Now, that knowledge, which is ours, is experiential, but it's not exhaustive.

25:05.493 --> 25:11.080
But his plan is that we might be filled with all the fullness of God.

25:13.263 --> 25:14.565
All the fullness of God.

25:14.705 --> 25:21.234
He's going to, in chapter 5, say, you shouldn't go and get drunk with wine and waste your life in that way.

25:21.570 --> 25:29.562
be filled with the Holy Spirit, and out of the fullness of God, then live your life, sing your praise, command the gospel.

25:29.602 --> 25:31.725
And this he prays for.

25:34.009 --> 25:35.491
Oh, it's so wonderful, isn't it?

25:35.511 --> 25:50.994
The hymn writer puts it, oh, fill me with thy fullness, Lord, until my very heart were flow in kindling thoughts and glowing words, you're loved to tell your praise to show.

25:52.898 --> 25:56.223
Well, very well, that's all under entreaty.

25:56.764 --> 26:07.720
What he asks, strength to know this in our inner being and power to grasp the immensity of God's love for us to be filled with his fullness.

26:08.762 --> 26:11.306
Well, if that's what he asks, on what basis does he ask?

26:11.826 --> 26:16.093
Well, the answer is in our title on the basis of God's generosity.

26:17.094 --> 26:19.278
And what he's telling us here is wonderful, isn't it?

26:20.119 --> 26:22.162
God is able to do what we ask.

26:22.946 --> 26:23.847
God is able.

26:24.468 --> 26:28.334
He's able to do what we think of asking, but aren't sure that we can.

26:28.394 --> 26:30.237
He is able.

26:30.798 --> 26:34.543
He is able to do far more than we ever thought of asking.

26:35.785 --> 26:45.459
In fact, there is nothing we can ask for or think of asking for about which God does not say, I'm able to do better than that.

26:48.584 --> 26:49.906
Romans 8, you know.

26:50.690 --> 26:53.973
What a wonder that having given up his son for us.

26:54.854 --> 27:00.219
Will he not also with him freely give us all things?

27:01.400 --> 27:09.448
And I guess that's why Jesus so masterfully encourages the disciples around him at that time arguing from the lesser to the greater.

27:09.468 --> 27:12.251
I mean, what a ridiculous idea, isn't it?

27:12.331 --> 27:13.392
It's almost humorous.

27:14.193 --> 27:19.378
You came down in the morning, yes, your father for a boiled egg, and he gave you a stone.

27:20.258 --> 27:23.863
Or he came down and asked for a sausage, and he gave you a serpent.

27:24.563 --> 27:27.127
You said to yourself, it couldn't possibly ever be.

27:27.167 --> 27:34.236
If even that were the case, even though you know that your parents are so generous, how much more?

27:34.516 --> 27:40.523
That God is far more willing to bless us than we are even to take the time to ask him.

27:42.206 --> 27:48.914
Newton, of course, when he discovered the reality of this, wrote out of the fullness of his own heart.

27:49.730 --> 27:54.017
Listen to him, come my soul thy suit repair.

27:55.519 --> 27:57.322
Jesus loves to answer prayer.

27:58.384 --> 28:04.433
He himself has bid thee pray, therefore will not say thee nay.

28:05.415 --> 28:17.874
Thou art coming to a king, large petitions with thee bring, for his grace and power are such that none can ever ask too much.

28:18.850 --> 28:40.179
Surely part of the reason for the loss of momentum in prayer gatherings, whether it's in your university or in your church, where there is a loss of momentum, it may be traced in part to the repetitive focus of the average midweek prayer meeting, which focuses again and again on the material and the physical.

28:40.980 --> 28:43.884
Of course, we can bring everything before God.

28:45.146 --> 28:48.370
But the problem in our prayers is not that

28:48.770 --> 28:54.555
We ask for things too great, or that our prayers are too big.

28:54.575 --> 29:04.024
The problem is that we're guilty of doubting God's ability and His generosity, and thus we become fearful of entreaty.

29:05.165 --> 29:09.630
I don't want to harm anybody in saying this, but let me just give you a word of exhortation.

29:10.931 --> 29:12.312
Well, maybe you shouldn't do it this way.

29:12.432 --> 29:14.154
Let me just give you the word of exhortation.

29:15.335 --> 29:18.578
Quit using the word just in your prayers.

29:20.482 --> 29:25.547
Or we're coming to you just, we just this, we just that, we just the next thing.

29:26.087 --> 29:29.330
It's an apologetic way of asking God.

29:29.450 --> 29:33.975
Like, we know that you don't really want to do this, so we're just asking.

29:34.375 --> 29:35.756
We're just wondering.

29:36.217 --> 29:41.021
There's no reason for just wondering or just doing it in that way at all.

29:41.442 --> 29:48.528
No, recognize the generosity of God and then come boldly.

29:49.789 --> 29:50.450
Remember?

29:50.722 --> 29:54.285
James says, you do not have because you do not ask.

29:55.066 --> 30:01.452
And when you ask, you don't receive because you ask wrongly to spend it on your passions.

30:03.054 --> 30:14.584
Love wants, if I could convince you of one thing, it surely must be what Paul is saying here, that in the great span of your life and the span of my life is hastening on, I can tell you.

30:15.285 --> 30:17.887
And this is where I am tonight in addressing you.

30:18.328 --> 30:20.690
Why would I receive the privilege of coming?

30:21.026 --> 30:32.682
because I'm in the position of the Samus in Psalm 71, and this is what he says, Oh God, from my youth you have taught me, and I still proclaim your wondrous deeds.

30:33.564 --> 30:44.619
So even to old age and gray hairs, Oh God, do not forsake me until I proclaim your might to another generation, your power to all those to come.

30:45.761 --> 30:47.543
You're sitting where I once sat.

30:48.344 --> 30:49.586
I'm the old man that

30:50.146 --> 30:54.110
I was listening to when I was 18 and 19 and 20.

30:54.150 --> 30:59.915
And then I listened carefully, being reminded of these amazing truths.

31:01.497 --> 31:17.452
Spurgeon, as he reflects on this, says of God, my master has riches beyond the count of arithmetic, the measurement of reason, the dream of imagination or of eloquence or of words.

31:18.233 --> 31:19.314
They are

31:19.618 --> 31:20.559
immeasurable.

31:21.801 --> 31:32.533
Or in the words of any Johnson flint, God's love has no limit, His grace has no measure, His power has no boundary known unto men.

31:33.875 --> 31:40.723
For out of His glorious riches in Jesus, He giveth, and giveth, and giveth again."

31:43.166 --> 31:45.409
Well, what does He ask?

31:45.449 --> 31:46.450
That's in treaty.

31:47.490 --> 31:48.411
On what basis?

31:48.651 --> 31:49.752
That's generosity.

31:49.772 --> 31:51.354
To what end?

31:52.255 --> 31:53.156
Well, that's glory.

31:54.397 --> 31:56.238
You notice how he finishes to him?

31:56.819 --> 31:57.460
Be glory.

31:57.580 --> 31:59.642
In the church, he ends with a doxology.

31:59.982 --> 32:05.287
Every so often in his letters, he breaks in essentially and starts singing, praising God.

32:05.808 --> 32:10.592
For a doxology is really just the theologically informed praise of God.

32:11.734 --> 32:16.338
And he concludes by praying that God will get all the glory

32:16.418 --> 32:17.259
he deserves.

32:18.260 --> 32:28.411
Just as God's glory has been his and will be revealed in Jesus, so his glory is revealed in his people in the church.

32:30.233 --> 32:46.130
Those believers in Ephesus reading this letter comprised Jewish Christians and Gentile Christians, called by God from couchers and identities that actually hated each other and were raised to be deeply suspicious of each other.

32:46.850 --> 32:47.852
And yet here they are.

32:48.172 --> 32:51.337
They meet and they sing and they pray together.

32:52.058 --> 33:07.843
And in that context, that which the world longs for is displayed amongst the people of God, in his power to transform in the wonder of his perfect compassion, his love being displayed.

33:09.206 --> 33:14.514
But it's not simply that God's glory is revealed in Jesus and displayed in the church.

33:14.754 --> 33:16.696
It is to be declared to the nations.

33:17.557 --> 33:18.979
This is a missions conference.

33:19.600 --> 33:26.569
Habakkuk looks forward to a day when the earth will be filled with the glory of God as the waters cover the sea.

33:27.550 --> 33:31.935
That huge vision is what took William Carey to India in 1793.

33:32.776 --> 33:43.890
That's what kept him going as God's plotter, when for it was seven years of him laboring before he ever baptized an Indian Christian.

33:44.258 --> 33:45.619
The same thing for C.T.

33:45.659 --> 33:50.664
Stud, who dedicated his life to foreign missions after reasoning this.

33:51.345 --> 34:01.034
If Jesus Christ be God and died for me, then no sacrifice that I could ever make for him could ever be too great.

34:02.135 --> 34:12.845
It is this which took John Payton from Scotland to the New Hebrides, a way out there, go to New Zealand and start looking for them somewhere out there.

34:13.205 --> 34:14.066
You'll find them.

34:15.202 --> 34:24.595
When he got there, a man by way of encouragement said to him, John, the cannibals, you will be eaten by cannibals.

34:26.318 --> 34:33.668
To which he said, eaten by cannibals or eaten by worms, what's the difference?

34:33.689 --> 34:37.394
I am here to declare the glory of the gospel.

34:38.515 --> 34:39.417
And here we are.

34:40.378 --> 34:43.122
This is now 24th century America.

34:44.450 --> 34:47.813
We represent all kinds of possibilities.

34:49.836 --> 34:52.739
All kinds of longings, hopes, dreams.

34:54.761 --> 34:56.843
You sit out there, I can't see you.

34:57.283 --> 34:58.104
It doesn't matter.

34:58.945 --> 34:59.846
God sees you.

35:00.747 --> 35:02.669
He's concerned about your inner being.

35:03.189 --> 35:06.312
He's concerned that you would be overwhelmed by his generosity.

35:06.813 --> 35:11.698
He's concerned that you would be prepared to say, you know, I'll give myself up for you.

35:13.602 --> 35:16.144
And the invitation to the church is to do just that.

35:17.386 --> 35:34.903
When town and in Getty wrote the hymn, more church arise, they wrote these words, when faced with trials of every kind, we know the outcome is secure, and Christ will have the prize for which He died, an inheritance of nations.

35:36.765 --> 35:42.290
So to Him be glory in the church and in Christ Jesus throughout all generations.

35:43.394 --> 35:44.836
Well, what about this generation?

35:46.218 --> 35:49.042
Do you believe that what God has done before he can do again?

35:49.063 --> 35:58.136
Your students of history, you know what it was like in 18th century England if you chose to look it up?

35:58.757 --> 36:00.540
You discover it was a dreadful place.

36:00.960 --> 36:03.064
It was a dark place, a godless place.

36:03.464 --> 36:06.689
People could be hanged for stealing a loaf of bread.

36:07.050 --> 36:12.658
Little children were in the most dreadful circumstances, and it was brutal.

36:14.114 --> 36:14.915
But what happened?

36:15.996 --> 36:27.628
God raised up two brothers by the name of Whitfield, raised up two brothers by the name of Wesley, a man by the name of Whitfield, and a Welshman by the name of Howl Harris.

36:28.629 --> 36:41.682
And in this space of some 60 years, there was a revolution that was brought about not by political energy, but was brought about by the transforming power of the generosity of God unleashed amongst his people.

36:42.274 --> 36:46.158
God is a specialist when it comes to the impossible.

36:47.119 --> 37:01.535
If God does not transform our culture in your generation by way of revival, it will not be because he can't, because he specializes in things thought impossible.

37:02.497 --> 37:04.939
How about you say, what are we going to do?

37:04.979 --> 37:07.822
All you old guys are dying off.

37:09.264 --> 37:11.026
We didn't hear from Carson.

37:11.682 --> 37:16.109
MacArthur's gone, Sproul's gone, Keller's gone.

37:17.371 --> 37:19.475
And some of you guys look like you're going as well.

37:20.216 --> 37:21.118
That's what you're saying.

37:21.158 --> 37:23.982
You're looking up, look at that old guy.

37:24.022 --> 37:27.929
Well, they said the same thing to J.C. Ryle.

37:27.949 --> 37:30.974
Incidentally, I hope you bought those volumes on J.C. Ryle $50.

37:31.475 --> 37:33.097
That is amazing.

37:33.117 --> 37:36.984
It's difficult for me as a Scotsman to see stuff given away so kindly.

37:37.685 --> 37:38.386
But anyway,

37:39.106 --> 37:42.990
They said to Ryle, what are we going to do now that all the good guys are dying?

37:43.391 --> 37:44.212
This is what he said.

37:45.493 --> 37:51.560
Fear not for the church of Christ when ministers die and saints are taken away.

37:52.541 --> 37:55.704
Christ can ever maintain his own cause.

37:56.685 --> 38:00.590
He will raise up better servants and brighter stars.

38:01.371 --> 38:04.114
The stars are in his right hand.

38:05.375 --> 38:08.178
Leave off all anxious thoughts about the future.

38:08.514 --> 38:15.004
cease to be cast down by the measures of statesmen or the plots of wolves in sheep's clothing.

38:15.926 --> 38:18.770
Christ will ever provide for his own church.

38:19.591 --> 38:23.978
Christ will take care that the gates of hell will not prevail against it.

38:25.040 --> 38:29.467
All is going well, though our eyes may not see it.

38:30.528 --> 38:36.658
The kingdoms of this world shall yet become the kingdoms of our God.

38:37.218 --> 38:38.440
and of his Christ.

38:40.003 --> 38:40.864
What does he ask?

38:43.208 --> 38:46.213
On what basis and to what end?

38:47.515 --> 38:48.136
Let us pray.

38:48.176 --> 39:04.082
Heavenly Father, we want to live our lives, earnestly desiring your will to be done, and that your name would be glorified.

39:04.994 --> 39:14.970
We want to live and die believing that in Jesus, we may receive grace upon grace beyond our asking or imagining.

39:16.453 --> 39:29.294
And tonight we pledge ourselves to be ready as instruments in your service, ready to go anywhere, anytime, anyhow.

39:30.876 --> 39:31.858
When we ask,

39:32.706 --> 39:37.031
that you will send out workers into your harvest.

39:37.051 --> 39:41.656
We are willing to be the answer to our own prayers.

39:43.538 --> 39:47.843
Lord, hear our prayers and let our cries come to you.

39:49.425 --> 39:52.128
In Jesus' name, amen.

